	title = {Recent warming reverses long-term {A}rctic cooling},
	author = "Kaufman, Darrell S and Schneider, David P and McKay, Nicholas P
               and Ammann, Caspar M and Bradley, Raymond S and Briffa, Keith R
               and Miller, Gifford H and Otto-Bliesner, Bette L and Overpeck,
               Jonathan T and Vinther, Bo M and {Arctic Lakes 2k Project
               Members}",
	abstract = "The temperature history of the first millennium C.E. is sparsely
               documented, especially in the Arctic. We present a synthesis of
               decadally resolved proxy temperature records from poleward of 60
               degrees N covering the past 2000 years, which indicates that a
               pervasive cooling in progress 2000 years ago continued through
               the Middle Ages and into the Little Ice Age. A 2000-year
               transient climate simulation with the Community Climate System
               Model shows the same temperature sensitivity to changes in
               insolation as does our proxy reconstruction, supporting the
               inference that this long-term trend was caused by the steady
               orbitally driven reduction in summer insolation. The cooling
               trend was reversed during the 20th century, with four of the
               five warmest decades of our 2000-year-long reconstruction
               occurring between 1950 and 2000.",
